class Solution {
    public boolean isSubsequence(String s, String t) {
        int sIndex = 0, tIndex = 0;
        while (sIndex < s.length() && tIndex < t.length()) {
            if (s.charAt(sIndex) == t.charAt(tIndex)) {
                sIndex++;
            }
            tIndex++;
        }
        return sIndex == s.length();
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through both strings once, using a two-pointer technique. It checks for matching characters and advances the pointer for string s only when a match is found. If all characters in s are matched in order, it returns true; otherwise, it returns false. For the follow-up scenario with multiple s strings, pre-processing t into a data structure like a hash map or trie could improve efficiency by allowing faster lookups.
